{"id":7966,"date":"2017-11-01T06:04:18","date_gmt":"2017-11-01T13:04:18","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/?p=7966"},"modified":"2025-08-08T16:17:03","modified_gmt":"2025-08-08T23:17:03","slug":"reco-mountain","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/11\/01\/reco-mountain\/","title":{"rendered":"RECO MOUNTAIN"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong><em>RECO MT<\/em>\u00a0\u00a0 <\/strong>2530m\u00a0\u00a0 8300\u2019\u2019<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><em>This trip was more of a drive up Reco Mountain Road (the only way I have been here) than a hike. But as the road deteriorates, there is more walking. I have driven to the pass from both sides in the old days, but now the road is not drivable from Cody and impassable 400m from the pass on the Stenson Creek side.<br \/>\nThe KMC register was removed in 2025 because there were so many visits, it was almost impossible to keep a book there &#8211; mountain bikers, motorcyclists, and many locals who loved the register book socially.\u00a0<\/em><\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Difficulty:<\/strong> B2<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Elevation gain:<\/strong> 680 m (2231&#8242;)<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Key elevations:<\/strong> End of drivable road 1800m (5900\u2019); Pass 2200m (7220\u2019); Summit Reco 2530m 8300\u2019<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Distance:<\/strong> 1.4km from pass. 9.9 km round trip\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Time:<\/strong><\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Season: <\/strong>July through September<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Access:<\/strong> Difficult 4WD HC up Stenson Creek<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Map:<\/strong> 82K\/14 Kokanee Glacier<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>\u00a0<\/strong><strong>Drive:<\/strong><br \/>\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Stenson Creek Road<\/span> \u2013 good access to the ridge and old mine at 1800m. From here it is a steep, washed-out mine road that leads to the pass at the base of Reco at 2200m that must be walked. Gets some traffic from ATVs but is not drivable by regular vehicles. Half the road is so steep you have to push, but the rest is enjoyable biking up through the alpine meadows and old mine workings. <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">From Cody &#8211; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Reco Mountain Road<\/span>. The road down the other side &#8211; Reco Mountain Road \u2013 goes to Cody and is steep tight switchbacks. An avalanche has thrown trees across the road, but a route is cut out by the ATVers. 2\/3 of the way down, the drivable road resumes and can zoom down the road to Sandon.<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Trail\/Route:<\/strong> From the pass, the summit of Reco Mt is an enjoyable stroll with flowers and great views.<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>What to do?<\/strong> <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> 1. Traverse over to <strong>Texas Peak<\/strong> \u2013 2 hours one-way from the pass to Texas.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">2. Climb <strong>Mt Payne<\/strong> (2276m 7467\u2019). Between Payne and Reco is \u201cMt Suffering\u201d. (this is an interesting section of the map \u2013 \u201cSuffering\u201d is exactly on the seam of 82F\/14 Kokanee Glacier and 82K\/3 Roseberry, and the entire route is covered by mining claims that make the elevation lines difficult to read \u2013 I believe it is over 1000\u2019 down to the col from Suffering and then a few hundred feet up to Payne).<\/span><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>RECO MT\u00a0\u00a0 2530m\u00a0\u00a0 8300\u2019\u2019 This trip was more of a drive up Reco Mountain Road (the only way I have been here) than a hike. But as the road deteriorates, there is more walking. I have driven to the pass &hellip; <a href=\"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/11\/01\/reco-mountain\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"jetpack_post_was_ever_published":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_access":"","_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id":0,"_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content":false,"_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content":false,"footnotes":"","jetpack_publicize_message":"","jetpack_publicize_feature_enabled":true,"jetpack_social_post_already_shared":true,"jetpack_social_options":{"image_generator_settings":{"template":"highway","default_image_id":0,"enabled":false},"version":2}},"categories":[1],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-7966","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","hentry","category-uncategorized"],"aioseo_notices":[],"jetpack_publicize_connections":[],"jetpack_featured_media_url":"","jetpack_sharing_enabled":true,"jetpack_shortlink":"https:\/\/wp.me\/p2Ncip-24u","_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/7966","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"h